reviewText: Down in Yankerville, it's a nice city where anything can happen and it's populated by puppet people who make crank calls to strangers yet with hilarious results. This show is a hilarious and shocking adult puppet show that aired on Comedy Central in 2002 and is now on MTV2, the show is created by Jimmy Kimmel, Daniel Kellison and Adam Carolla with some guest stars like Wanda Sykes, Dave Chappell, Sarah Silverman, David Alan Grier, Tracey Morgan, Billy West, Superdave Osbourne, Jack Black, Ween, and Dennis Leary doing actual prank phone calls to actual people as they are recorded and portrayed by puppets like the Sesame Street kind.Here on this season features skits like Wanda who complaints about a human log in the backseat of her car, some unfriendly UPS fellows especially Willy, lovable grandpa-esque old man Elmer, retarded fellow Ed, flamboyant millionaire Niles, and other hilarious goodies. It may not be for everyone but it's a damn good comedy puppet show for adults.This DVD has the show uncensored with puppet nudity and vulger language which were censored with a couple of extras like two unaired calls and a documentary behind this show.
summary: One of the funniest shows i've ever seen!

reviewText: Unlike some people, I don't review DVDs until I have actually watched them.  This collection includes all 10 first seasons episodes of Crank Yankers, now with the curse words unbleeped.  There are still a few bleeps, though; mostly the names of businesses.  Like when Terrence calls Spago to make a reservation for Bill Cosby, "Spago" is bleeped.  Oddly, though, on theCD versionof that call, "Spago" was unbleeped.  Watching the early episodes of Crank Yankers, it is interesting to observe some of the ways the show has "evolved" since then.  Some of the puppets didn't have quite the same look as they do now.  The most notable difference is in Cammie, who was originally a blonde.  Also, the show was more experimental during the first season.  They tried things like having musical performances and "wise sayings" from Confucius.  These bits were later dropped to concentrate entirely on the crank phone calls.  The bonus materials on the DVD include a documentary about the making of the show, which is interesting, at least the first time you watch it.  There are also two unaired calls, which are not as funny as the calls that actually did air.  If you like this show, this DVD set is well produced and worth the money.

reviewText: Crank Yankers is a great muppet looking type of show for the.... ummm.... more mature audience..... umm, no... lets just say it's not a kids show. A group of actors make (100% real) prank phone calls to unsuspecting suvillians and then the recorded conversation is then presented visualy with the puppets that reside in Yankerville.All 10 episodes from season 1 are presented on 2 discs with 2 un-aired sketches and a documentry with some behind the scenes footage and shows you who the actors are playing the crank calling roles.I do like the Crank Yankers, but season 1 was not the best, however it does have some pretty darn funny moments. But this DVD release could have been so much more. A pet peeve I have about the presentation tho is that it is 2 discs, and I am left wondering, why? On disc 1 there is 5 episodes that go for about an hour and 30 minintes. and about 5 short clips of other Comedy Chanel preveiws. Then on disc 2 there is the next 5 shows at the same length and 2 lousy sketches that wernt aired for good reason that are about 4 minutes each, and the documentry that goes for about 20 minutes. And all the preveiws combined could last more then 10 to 15 maybe 20 minutes. All of those combined are under 4 hours, a DVD will hold 4 hours of good standard quality. So why is it on 2 discs??? Also I hate the 2 seperate slim cases it comes in, inside of a cardboard box.There isnt enough bonus footage included ont hese. The first sketch was not funny, the second one wasnt either, the documentry is ok, but we need much, much more to make this DVD super. At least the sketches are unsensoured, so there is no bleeping out words. It would have been real nice to have an option to not only just veiw the episodes individualy or all together, but have an option to view just the same charactor. I'd like to be able to just pick my favorite charactor (Special Ed) and just veiw his pranks continusly. I can't beleive there was only about 2 or 3 special ED pranks in season 1. Lets hope they have more to offer on season 2.
summary: Not the best it could have been for a DVD release

reviewText: I used to make prank calls as a kid, and I have to admit I am jealous of the Crank Yankers.  They put so much time and effort into it.  They do tons of research, and it is absolutely hilarious.  I have a dark sense of humor, and the thing I like the most is how hateful a lot of these calls are.  The Crank Yankers are so mean.  The characters don't really need a description, it is better to be surprised.  The actors who make the calls include Jimmy Kimmel, Sarah Silverman, Super Dave Osborne, Kevin Nealon, and Jim Florentine plays Special Ed and the extremely rude Bobby Fletcher.  My personal favorite calls are the incoming calls where people think they dialed the number for UPS.  The Touchtone Terrorists are THE best prank callers, so be sure to check out their CDs if you get a chance.  They are just as good, if not better than the Crank Yankers.If you need a really good laugh, this is exactly what you are looking for.Special features are interesting.  There are 2 un-aired calls, and a 26 minute making of that I enjoyed very much.
summary: Have you ever made a prank all?  If you have, then you will love this

reviewText: Crank Yankers.A show that only that Adam Carolla and Jimmy Kimmel could get away with making.The show blends live action puppetry acting out fake crank calls.  The concept is so bad its amazing it has lasted more than one season. However, being on Comedy Central explains how its been able to last. Since CC isn't exactly the beacon of intelligent comedy.The whole premise - crank calls is weak and lame. Anyone of voting age with the appropriate level of maturity can't get to the remote fast enough to change the channel.  You have attempted humor with a mentally challenged invidual yelling "I Got Mail" at the subject repeatidly on the other end of the line or another case of a man who repeatedly vomits into the phone during his prank call. Then there are your typical sex shop crank calls and they are lame too. The whole show is simply not funny.I'll go one step further too. Crank Calls are the cheapest attempt at humor in existance. To set someone up who has no clue what your doing then think its funny that they are either too polite and won't hang up or can't tell you to eff off is lame.Bottom line - funny to 10 year olds thats about it. Avoid this stinker.
summary: The Worst TV I've ever seen - A total steaming pile
